455.answer:
A callback “missing return” bug usually happens when you use braces in an arrow function but forget to explicitly return a value.

### Why it happens

This works:

```js
const nums = [1, 2, 3].map(x => x * 2);
```

But this does **not**:

```js
const nums = [1, 2, 3].map(x => {
  x * 2;
});
```

Because with `{ ... }`, the callback body is a block, so JavaScript won’t return automatically. That callback returns `undefined` for every item.

### Fix

Add `return`:

```js
const nums = [1, 2, 3].map(x => {
  return x * 2;
});
```

Or use the concise form:

```js
const nums = [1, 2, 3].map(x => x * 2);
```

### Common cases

#### `map`
```js
const names = users.map(user => {
  return user.name;
});
```

#### `filter`
```js
const adults = users.filter(user => {
  return user.age >= 18;
});
```

#### `find`
```js
const admin = users.find(user => {
  return user.role === 'admin';
});
```

### One more common gotcha

Returning an object literal needs parentheses:

```js
const items = users.map(user => ({ id: user.id, name: user.name }));
```

Without parentheses, JS treats `{}` as a block, not an object.

