This usually happens when `||` is used where `&&` is required.

### Bug pattern
```js
function isValid(status) {
  if (status !== 'open' || status !== 'closed') {
    return true;
  }
}
```

This **always returns true**, because `status` cannot be both `'open'` and `'closed'` at the same time:

- if `status === 'open'`, then `status !== 'closed'` is true
- if `status === 'closed'`, then `status !== 'open'` is true
- anything else also makes both true

### Fix
Use `&&` so both “not equal” checks must be true:

```js
function isValid(status) {
  if (status !== 'open' && status !== 'closed') {
    return true;
  }
  return false;
}
```

Or more simply:

```js
function isValid(status) {
  return status !== 'open' && status !== 'closed';
}
```

