473.answer:
Direct equality fails because many decimal values can’t be represented exactly in binary floating point.

```js
0.1 + 0.2 === 0.3 // false
```

`0.1 + 0.2` is actually something like `0.30000000000000004`, so the condition fails.

Use an epsilon/tolerance comparison instead:

```js
function nearlyEqual(a, b, epsilon = 1e-10) {
  return Math.abs(a - b) < epsilon;
}

if (nearlyEqual(0.1 + 0.2, 0.3)) {
  console.log("equal");
}
```

If you want a one-liner:

```js
if (Math.abs((0.1 + 0.2) - 0.3) < 1e-10) {
  console.log("equal");
}
```

For larger/smaller magnitudes, a relative comparison is more robust:

```js
function nearlyEqual(a, b, epsilon = 1e-10) {
  return Math.abs(a - b) <= epsilon * Math.max(1, Math.abs(a), Math.abs(b));
}
```

