  if (nums.length === 1) return 0;

  for (let i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
    const left = i === 0 ? -Infinity : nums[i - 1];
    const right = i === 0 ? nums[i + 1] : (i === nums.length - 1 ? -Infinity : nums[i + 1]);

    if (nums[i] >= left && nums[i] >= right) {
      return i;
    }
  }

  return -1;
}
```

### Tie handling
A peak is any element `nums[i]` such that:

- `nums[i] >= nums[i - 1]` if a left neighbor exists
- `nums[i] >= nums[i + 1]` if a right neighbor exists

So equal adjacent values **can count as a peak**.  
If multiple peaks exist, this function returns the **first** one it finds.

