A **priority queue** stores items so you can always remove the item with the **highest priority** efficiently. In a **min-priority queue**, the smallest value has the highest priority.

A **heap** is a great fit because it keeps the priority queue partially ordered:

- In a **min-heap**, every parent is `<=` its children.
- That means the **smallest element is always at the root**.
- So:
  - **insert** adds a new item at the end, then “bubbles up” until heap order is restored.
  - **extractMin** removes the root, moves the last item to the root, then “bubbles down” until heap order is restored.

Using an array makes this efficient:

- left child of index `i` → `2*i + 1`
- right child of index `i` → `2*i + 2`
- parent of index `i` → `Math.floor((i - 1) / 2)`

### Time complexity
- `insert`: **O(log n)**
- `extractMin`: **O(log n)**
- `peek`: **O(1)**

## JavaScript min-heap class

```js
class MinHeap {
  constructor() {
    this.heap = [];
  }

  insert(value) {
    this.heap.push(value);
    this.bubbleUp(this.heap.length - 1);
  }

  extractMin() {
    if (this.heap.length === 0) return null;
    if (this.heap.length === 1) return this.heap.pop();

    const min = this.heap[0];
    this.heap[0] = this.heap.pop();
    this.bubbleDown(0);
    return min;
  }

  bubbleUp(index) {
    while (index > 0) {
      const parentIndex = Math.floor((index - 1) / 2);

      if (this.heap[parentIndex] <= this.heap[index]) break;

      [this.heap[parentIndex], this.heap[index]] = [this.heap[index], this.heap[parentIndex]];
      index = parentIndex;
    }
  }

  bubbleDown(index) {
    const length = this.heap.length;

    while (true) {
      let smallest = index;
      const left = 2 * index + 1;
      const right = 2 * index + 2;

      if (left < length && this.heap[left] < this.heap[smallest]) {
        smallest = left;
      }

      if (right < length && this.heap[right] < this.heap[smallest]) {
        smallest = right;
      }

      if (smallest === index) break;

      [this.heap[index], this.heap[smallest]] = [this.heap[smallest], this.heap[index]];
      index = smallest;
    }
  }
}
```

## Example usage

```js
const pq = new MinHeap();

pq.insert(5);
pq.insert(2);
pq.insert(8);
pq.insert(1);

console.log(pq.extractMin()); // 1
console.log(pq.extractMin()); // 2
console.log(pq.extractMin()); // 5
console.log(pq.extractMin()); // 8
```

