A **trie** (pronounced “try”), or **prefix tree**, is a tree-like data structure used to store strings so that **common prefixes are shared**.

### What problem it solves
A trie is useful when you need to do lots of string lookups involving prefixes, such as:

- checking whether a word exists
- checking whether any word starts with a prefix
- autocomplete
- dictionary/spell-check features
- prefix-based filtering

### Why use a trie instead of a hash set
With a hash set:
- `search("cat")` is fast
- but `startsWith("ca")` is not naturally supported

With a trie:
- `insert("cat")`
- `search("cat")`
- `startsWith("ca")`

are all efficient, typically **O(L)** where `L` is the length of the word/prefix.

### How it works
Each node represents a character.  
A path from the root to a node represents a prefix.  
A flag like `isEnd` marks whether a full word ends there.

If you insert:

- `"cat"`
- `"car"`

they share the path:

`c -> a`

and then branch into:

- `t`
- `r`

---

## JavaScript Trie class

```js
class TrieNode {
  constructor() {
    this.children = new Map();
    this.isEnd = false;
  }
}

class Trie {
  constructor() {
    this.root = new TrieNode();
  }

  insert(word) {
    let node = this.root;

    for (const char of word) {
      if (!node.children.has(char)) {
        node.children.set(char, new TrieNode());
      }
      node = node.children.get(char);
    }

    node.isEnd = true;
  }

  search(word) {
    const node = this._traverse(word);
    return node !== null && node.isEnd;
  }

  startsWith(prefix) {
    return this._traverse(prefix) !== null;
  }

  _traverse(str) {
    let node = this.root;

    for (const char of str) {
      if (!node.children.has(char)) {
        return null;
      }
      node = node.children.get(char);
    }

    return node;
  }
}
```

## Example usage

```js
const trie = new Trie();

trie.insert("apple");

console.log(trie.search("apple"));    // true
console.log(trie.search("app"));      // false
console.log(trie.startsWith("app"));  // true

trie.insert("app");
console.log(trie.search("app"));      // true
```

