A **hash table** stores key-value pairs and aims for near-constant-time lookup, insert, and delete.

### Core idea
1. Take a key, like `"apple"`.
2. Run it through a **hash function** to turn it into a number.
3. Use that number to choose an index in an array.
4. Store the entry there.

### Why it’s fast
If the hash function spreads keys evenly, operations are usually:
- **Insert:** `O(1)` average
- **Lookup:** `O(1)` average
- **Delete:** `O(1)` average

Worst case can degrade to `O(n)` if many keys collide.

### Collisions
Different keys can hash to the same bucket. Common strategies:

- **Separate chaining:** each bucket stores a list of entries
- **Open addressing:** probe for another empty slot

You asked for **separate chaining**, so each array slot holds a small array of `[key, value]` pairs.

### Important pieces
- **Buckets:** underlying array
- **Hash function:** maps a string key to a bucket index
- **Load factor:** `size / bucketCount`; high load factor means more collisions
- **Resize/Rehash:** when too full, allocate more buckets and reinsert entries

---

## Simple separate-chaining hash map in JavaScript

Supports:
- string keys
- integer values

```js
class HashMap {
  constructor(initialCapacity = 16) {
    this.buckets = Array.from({ length: initialCapacity }, () => []);
    this.size = 0;
  }

  _hash(key) {
    let hash = 0;
    for (let i = 0; i < key.length; i++) {
      hash = (hash * 31 + key.charCodeAt(i)) >>> 0;
    }
    return hash % this.buckets.length;
  }

  _resize() {
    const oldBuckets = this.buckets;
    this.buckets = Array.from({ length: oldBuckets.length * 2 }, () => []);
    this.size = 0;

    for (const bucket of oldBuckets) {
      for (const [key, value] of bucket) {
        this.set(key, value);
      }
    }
  }

  set(key, value) {
    if (typeof key !== "string") {
      throw new TypeError("Key must be a string");
    }
    if (!Number.isInteger(value)) {
      throw new TypeError("Value must be an integer");
    }

    const index = this._hash(key);
    const bucket = this.buckets[index];

    for (let i = 0; i < bucket.length; i++) {
      if (bucket[i][0] === key) {
        bucket[i][1] = value;
        return;
      }
    }

    bucket.push([key, value]);
    this.size++;

    if (this.size / this.buckets.length > 0.75) {
      this._resize();
    }
  }

  get(key) {
    if (typeof key !== "string") {
      throw new TypeError("Key must be a string");
    }

    const index = this._hash(key);
    const bucket = this.buckets[index];

    for (const [entryKey, value] of bucket) {
      if (entryKey === key) {
        return value;
      }
    }

    return undefined;
  }

  has(key) {
    return this.get(key) !== undefined;
  }

  delete(key) {
    if (typeof key !== "string") {
      throw new TypeError("Key must be a string");
    }

    const index = this._hash(key);
    const bucket = this.buckets[index];

    for (let i = 0; i < bucket.length; i++) {
      if (bucket[i][0] === key) {
        bucket.splice(i, 1);
        this.size--;
        return true;
      }
    }

    return false;
  }

  entries() {
    const result = [];
    for (const bucket of this.buckets) {
      for (const entry of bucket) {
        result.push([...entry]);
      }
    }
    return result;
  }
}
```

## Example usage

```js
const map = new HashMap();

map.set("apple", 5);
map.set("banana", 3);
map.set("apple", 10);

console.log(map.get("apple"));   // 10
console.log(map.get("banana"));  // 3
console.log(map.get("pear"));    // undefined

console.log(map.has("banana"));  // true
console.log(map.delete("banana"));// true
console.log(map.has("banana"));  // false

console.log(map.entries());      // [ [ 'apple', 10 ] ]
console.log(map.size);           // 1
```

## Notes
- This is intentionally simple, not production-grade.
- `has()` uses `get() !== undefined`, which is fine here because values are restricted to integers, so `undefined` is never a valid stored value.
- Real implementations often use better hash functions and more optimized resizing behavior.

