A **monotonic queue** is a queue that keeps its elements in sorted order as you push and pop, usually either:

- **decreasing** for window maximums
- **increasing** for window minimums

For the **sliding window maximum** problem, we use a **decreasing deque**:

- The **front** always holds the index of the current maximum.
- When adding a new element:
  - Remove elements from the back while they are **smaller than or equal to** the new value.
  - Then push the new index.
- When moving the window:
  - Remove the front if it is outside the current window.

This works because any smaller element behind a larger new element can never become the maximum of a future window.

## Why it’s efficient

Each index is:

- pushed once
- popped at most once

So the total time is **O(n)**, much better than recomputing each window maximum in **O(k)**.

---

## JavaScript implementation

Your prompt is missing the window size value after `size .`, so I’ll implement a general function that takes `k`.

```js
function maxSlidingWindow(nums, k) {
  if (!nums.length || k === 0) return [];

  const deque = []; // stores indices, values are in decreasing order
  const result = [];

  for (let i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
    // Remove indices that are out of this window
    if (deque.length && deque[0] <= i - k) {
      deque.shift();
    }

    // Maintain decreasing order in deque
    while (deque.length && nums[deque[deque.length - 1]] <= nums[i]) {
      deque.pop();
    }

    deque.push(i);

    // Start recording answers once the first window is formed
    if (i >= k - 1) {
      result.push(nums[deque[0]]);
    }
  }

  return result;
}
```

## Example

```js
console.log(maxSlidingWindow([1,3,-1,-3,5,3,6,7], 3));
// [3, 3, 5, 5, 6, 7]
```

## Step-by-step intuition

For `nums = [1,3,-1,-3,5,3,6,7]`, `k = 3`:

- Window `[1,3,-1]` → max is `3`
- Window `[3,-1,-3]` → max is `3`
- Window `[-1,-3,5]` → max is `5`
- Window `[-3,5,3]` → max is `5`
- Window `[5,3,6]` → max is `6`
- Window `[3,6,7]` → max is `7`

---

## If you want a reusable MonotonicQueue class

```js
class MonotonicQueue {
  constructor() {
    this.q = [];
  }

  push(value) {
    while (this.q.length && this.q[this.q.length - 1] < value) {
      this.q.pop();
    }
    this.q.push(value);
  }

  max() {
    return this.q[0];
  }

  pop(value) {
    if (this.q.length && this.q[0] === value) {
      this.q.shift();
    }
  }
}

function maxSlidingWindow(nums, k) {
  if (!nums.length || k === 0) return [];

  const mq = new MonotonicQueue();
  const result = [];

  for (let i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
    mq.push(nums[i]);

    if (i >= k - 1) {
      result.push(mq.max());
      mq.pop(nums[i - k + 1]);
    }
  }

  return result;
}
```

