789.answer:
The **Strategy Pattern** is a behavioral design pattern that lets you define a family of algorithms, put each one in its own class/object, and make them interchangeable at runtime.

### Why use it
Use it when:
- you have multiple ways to do the same thing
- you want to switch behavior without `if/else` chains everywhere
- you want code that is easier to extend

### Core idea
Instead of writing one big payment processor like:

```js
if (method === "creditCard") {
  // ...
} else if (method === "paypal") {
  // ...
} else if (method === "bankTransfer") {
  // ...
}
```

you define separate strategies:
- `CreditCardPayment`
- `PayPalPayment`
- `BankTransferPayment`

Then a context object uses whichever strategy is provided.

---

## JavaScript example

```js
class CreditCardPayment {
  pay(amount) {
    console.log(`Paid $${amount} using Credit Card.`);
  }
}

class PayPalPayment {
  pay(amount) {
    console.log(`Paid $${amount} using PayPal.`);
  }
}

class BankTransferPayment {
  pay(amount) {
    console.log(`Paid $${amount} using Bank Transfer.`);
  }
}

class PaymentProcessor {
  constructor(strategy) {
    this.strategy = strategy;
  }

  setStrategy(strategy) {
    this.strategy = strategy;
  }

  processPayment(amount) {
    if (!this.strategy || typeof this.strategy.pay !== "function") {
      throw new Error("A valid payment strategy must be provided.");
    }

    this.strategy.pay(amount);
  }
}

// Usage
const processor = new PaymentProcessor(new CreditCardPayment());
processor.processPayment(100);

processor.setStrategy(new PayPalPayment());
processor.processPayment(200);

processor.setStrategy(new BankTransferPayment());
processor.processPayment(300);
```

---

## Output

```js
Paid $100 using Credit Card.
Paid $200 using PayPal.
Paid $300 using Bank Transfer.
```

---

## How this shows the Strategy Pattern
- `CreditCardPayment`, `PayPalPayment`, and `BankTransferPayment` are the **strategies**
- `PaymentProcessor` is the **context**
- `processPayment()` delegates the work to the current strategy
- you can swap strategies at runtime with `setStrategy()`

---

## Slightly more realistic version

If you want each strategy to hold its own data:

```js
class CreditCardPayment {
  constructor(cardNumber) {
    this.cardNumber = cardNumber;
  }

  pay(amount) {
    console.log(`Paid $${amount} using Credit Card ending in ${this.cardNumber.slice(-4)}.`);
  }
}

class PayPalPayment {
  constructor(email) {
    this.email = email;
  }

  pay(amount) {
    console.log(`Paid $${amount} using PayPal account ${this.email}.`);
  }
}

class BankTransferPayment {
  constructor(accountNumber) {
    this.accountNumber = accountNumber;
  }

  pay(amount) {
    console.log(`Paid $${amount} using Bank Transfer from account ending in ${this.accountNumber.slice(-4)}.`);
  }
}

class PaymentProcessor {
  constructor(strategy) {
    this.strategy = strategy;
  }

  setStrategy(strategy) {
    this.strategy = strategy;
  }

  processPayment(amount) {
    if (!this.strategy || typeof this.strategy.pay !== "function") {
      throw new Error("A valid payment strategy must be provided.");
    }

    this.strategy.pay(amount);
  }
}

// Usage
const processor = new PaymentProcessor(
  new CreditCardPayment("1234567812345678")
);
processor.processPayment(150);

processor.setStrategy(new PayPalPayment("user@example.com"));
processor.processPayment(75);

processor.setStrategy(new BankTransferPayment("987654321234"));
processor.processPayment(500);
```

If you want, I can also show the same pattern using:
1. **plain objects instead of classes**, or
2. **TypeScript with interfaces**.

