The **Factory Method** pattern is a creational design pattern that defines an interface for creating objects, while letting subclasses or helper classes decide which concrete implementation to instantiate.

### Why use it
Instead of writing code like:

```java
if (type.equals("email")) {
    return new EmailSender();
} else if (type.equals("sms")) {
    return new SmsSender();
}
```

you centralize object creation in one place. This makes the code:
- easier to extend
- cleaner to maintain
- less coupled to concrete classes

### Structure
- **Product interface**: common behavior
- **Concrete products**: specific implementations
- **Factory**: creates the right product based on input

---

## Java example: Notification Senders

```java
interface NotificationSender {
    void send(String recipient, String message);
}

class EmailSender implements NotificationSender {
    @Override
    public void send(String recipient, String message) {
        System.out.println("Sending EMAIL to " + recipient + ": " + message);
    }
}

class SmsSender implements NotificationSender {
    @Override
    public void send(String recipient, String message) {
        System.out.println("Sending SMS to " + recipient + ": " + message);
    }
}

class PushSender implements NotificationSender {
    @Override
    public void send(String recipient, String message) {
        System.out.println("Sending PUSH notification to " + recipient + ": " + message);
    }
}

class NotificationFactory {
    public static NotificationSender createSender(String type) {
        if (type == null) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Notification type cannot be null");
        }

        switch (type.toLowerCase()) {
            case "email":
                return new EmailSender();
            case "sms":
                return new SmsSender();
            case "push":
                return new PushSender();
            default:
                throw new IllegalArgumentException("Unknown notification type: " + type);
        }
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        NotificationSender emailSender = NotificationFactory.createSender("email");
        emailSender.send("alice@example.com", "Welcome via email");

        NotificationSender smsSender = NotificationFactory.createSender("sms");
        smsSender.send("+1234567890", "Your OTP is 123456");

        NotificationSender pushSender = NotificationFactory.createSender("push");
        pushSender.send("user-device-token", "You have a new alert");
    }
}
```

---

## Output
```java
Sending EMAIL to alice@example.com: Welcome via email
Sending SMS to +1234567890: Your OTP is 123456
Sending PUSH notification to user-device-token: You have a new alert
```

## Benefits here
- `Main` depends only on `NotificationSender`, not concrete classes
- adding a new sender like `WhatsAppSender` is straightforward
- creation logic stays in `NotificationFactory`

If you want, I can also show the **classic GoF version** with an abstract creator class and concrete factory subclasses.

791.answer:
The **singleton pattern** ensures a class has **exactly one instance** and provides a **global access point** to it.

### When to use it
Use a singleton when:
- only one shared instance should exist
- creating multiple instances would be wasteful or incorrect
- you want centralized coordination, like:
  - logging
  - configuration
  - cache managers
  - service registries

### Key characteristics
- **private constructor** prevents external instantiation
- **static instance access** exposes the single object
- often includes **lazy initialization** so the instance is created only when first used
- in multithreaded apps, it must be **thread-safe**

### Pros
- controlled single instance
- easy shared access
- can reduce repeated setup cost

### Cons
- introduces global state
- can make testing harder
- can hide dependencies if overused

## Thread-safe singleton logger in C#

The simplest modern approach is to use `Lazy<T>`, which is thread-safe by default.

```csharp
using System;
using System.IO;

public sealed class Logger
{
    private static readonly Lazy<Logger> _instance =
        new Lazy<Logger>(() => new Logger());

    private readonly string _logFilePath;
    private readonly object _writeLock = new object();

    private Logger()
    {
        _logFilePath = Path.Combine(AppDomain.CurrentDomain.BaseDirectory, "app.log");
    }

    public static Logger Instance => _instance.Value;

    public void Log(string message)
    {
        string entry = $"[{DateTime.Now:yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss}] {message}{Environment.NewLine}";

        lock (_writeLock)
        {
            File.AppendAllText(_logFilePath, entry);
        }
    }
}
```

## Example usage

```csharp
class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        Logger.Instance.Log("Application started");
        Logger.Instance.Log("Processing request");
        Logger.Instance.Log("Application finished");
    }
}
```

## Why this is thread-safe
- `Lazy<Logger>` guarantees only one instance is created, even across threads
- `lock (_writeLock)` prevents concurrent file writes from corrupting the log

## Alternative: eager initialization
If lazy loading is unnecessary, this is also thread-safe in C# because static initialization is thread-safe:

```csharp
public sealed class Logger
{
    private static readonly Logger _instance = new Logger();

    private Logger() { }

    public static Logger Instance => _instance;
}
```

