- a version with **log levels** (`Info`, `Warn`, `Error`)
- a version using **dependency injection instead of singleton**

793.answer:
The **Adapter pattern** lets incompatible interfaces work together without changing the existing code.

### When to use it
Use it when:
- you have an existing class/service with the “wrong” interface
- new code expects a different interface
- rewriting the legacy service is risky or expensive

### Core idea
You wrap the legacy implementation in an **adapter** that exposes the interface your app wants.

- **Target**: the interface your app expects
- **Adaptee**: the existing legacy service
- **Adapter**: converts between them

---

## Example scenario

You have a legacy service that returns XML like:

```xml
<user>
  <id>42</id>
  <name>Ada</name>
  <email>ada@example.com</email>
</user>
```

But your modern app expects JSON like:

```ts
{
  id: 42,
  name: "Ada",
  email: "ada@example.com"
}
```

---

## TypeScript implementation

```ts
// Target interface: what the new application expects
interface UserService {
  getUser(id: number): Promise<User>;
}

type User = {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  email: string;
};

// Adaptee: legacy XML service
class LegacyXmlUserService {
  async fetchUserXml(id: number): Promise<string> {
    // Simulated legacy XML response
    return `
      <user>
        <id>${id}</id>
        <name>Ada Lovelace</name>
        <email>ada@example.com</email>
      </user>
    `;
  }
}

// Adapter: converts XML service output into JSON objects
class XmlToJsonUserServiceAdapter implements UserService {
  constructor(private legacyService: LegacyXmlUserService) {}

  async getUser(id: number): Promise<User> {
    const xml = await this.legacyService.fetchUserXml(id);
    return this.parseUserXml(xml);
  }

  private parseUserXml(xml: string): User {
    const getTagValue = (tag: string): string => {
      const match = xml.match(new RegExp(`<${tag}>(.*?)</${tag}>`, "s"));
      if (!match) {
        throw new Error(`Missing <${tag}> in XML response`);
      }
      return match[1].trim();
    };

    return {
      id: Number(getTagValue("id")),
      name: getTagValue("name"),
      email: getTagValue("email"),
    };
  }
}

// Client code only depends on the target interface
async function main() {
  const legacyService = new LegacyXmlUserService();
  const userService: UserService = new XmlToJsonUserServiceAdapter(legacyService);

  const user = await userService.getUser(42);
  console.log(user);
}

main();
```

---

## Output

```ts
{
  id: 42,
  name: "Ada Lovelace",
  email: "ada@example.com"
}
```

---

## Why this is useful
Benefits:
- keeps legacy code unchanged
- isolates format conversion in one place
- lets modern code depend on clean interfaces
- makes future replacement easier

Tradeoff:
- adds an extra layer/class

---

## Real-world version with a JSON string interface

If you want the adapter to return raw JSON-compatible data from XML:

```ts
interface JsonApi {
  getUser(id: number): Promise<Record<string, unknown>>;
}

class LegacyXmlService {
  async getUserData(id: number): Promise<string> {
    return `<user><id>${id}</id><name>Grace Hopper</name><email>grace@example.com</email></user>`;
  }
}

class XmlToJsonAdapter implements JsonApi {
  constructor(private xmlService: LegacyXmlService) {}

  async getUser(id: number): Promise<Record<string, unknown>> {
    const xml = await this.xmlService.getUserData(id);

    const read = (tag: string) => {
      const match = xml.match(new RegExp(`<${tag}>(.*?)</${tag}>`, "s"));
      return match?.[1]?.trim() ?? null;
    };

    return {
      id: Number(read("id")),
      name: read("name"),
      email: read("email"),
    };
  }
}
```

