const existing = ['ℌ𝔢𝔩𝔩𝔬', 'User１', 'Ａlice'];

console.log(validateUsername('Hello', existing));
// invalid if NFKC makes both map to "hello"

console.log(validateUsername('User1', existing));
// invalid if "User１" normalizes to "user1"

console.log(validateUsername('Alice', existing));
// invalid if "Ａlice" normalizes to "alice"
```

If you want stricter spoof protection, add a confusables skeleton step on top of NFKC, but for your stated requirement, comparing the normalized canonical identifier is enough.

