Use a real CSV parser or a state machine. Splitting on `\n` or `,` will break on quoted fields.

### Rules to handle
- commas inside quotes are literal field content
- newlines inside quotes are part of the field
- `""` inside a quoted field means a literal `"`
- empty fields are valid: `a,,b`
- Unicode commas like `，` are just normal characters unless you explicitly choose them as delimiters

### Example implementation in JavaScript

```js
function parseCSV(input, delimiter = ',') {
  const rows = [];
  let row = [];
  let field = '';
  let i = 0;
  let inQuotes = false;

  while (i < input.length) {
    const char = input[i];

    if (inQuotes) {
      if (char === '"') {
        if (input[i + 1] === '"') {
          field += '"';
          i += 2;
          continue;
        }
        inQuotes = false;
        i++;
        continue;
      }

      field += char;
      i++;
      continue;
    }

    if (char === '"') {
      inQuotes = true;
      i++;
      continue;
    }

    if (char === delimiter) {
      row.push(field);
      field = '';
      i++;
      continue;
    }

    if (char === '\n') {
      row.push(field);
      rows.push(row);
      row = [];
      field = '';
      i++;
      continue;
    }

    if (char === '\r') {
      if (input[i + 1] === '\n') i++;
      row.push(field);
      rows.push(row);
      row = [];
      field = '';
      i++;
      continue;
    }

    field += char;
    i++;
  }

  row.push(field);
  rows.push(row);

  return rows;
}
```

### Example

```js
const input = `name,notes,score
"Alice","hello
world",10
"Bob","said ""hi""", 
"陈明","uses unicode comma ， here",42
,,`;

console.log(parseCSV(input));
```

### Output

```js
[
  ['name', 'notes', 'score'],
  ['Alice', 'hello\nworld', '10'],
  ['Bob', 'said "hi"', ' '],
  ['陈明', 'uses unicode comma ， here', '42'],
  ['', '', '']
]
```

### Notes
- This assumes standard CSV escaping with `"` as quote char.
- If you need strict RFC 4180 behavior, malformed input should raise an error when quotes are unbalanced.
- In production, prefer a battle-tested library:
  - Node: `csv-parse`, `papaparse`
  - Python: built-in `csv`

