Use **end-of-month clamping**:

- Add 1 to the month.
- If the target month has the same day number, keep it.
- If not, use the **last day of the target month**.

Example behavior:
- **2023-01-31 + 1 month = 2023-02-28**
- **2024-01-31 + 1 month = 2024-02-29** (leap year)
- **2024-03-31 + 1 month = 2024-04-30**
- **2024-02-29 + 1 month = 2024-03-29**

JavaScript example with tests:

```js
function addOneCalendarMonth(date) {
  const year = date.getFullYear();
  const month = date.getMonth(); // 0-based
  const day = date.getDate();

  const targetYear = month === 11 ? year + 1 : year;
  const targetMonth = (month + 1) % 12;

  const lastDayOfTargetMonth = new Date(targetYear, targetMonth + 1, 0).getDate();
  const clampedDay = Math.min(day, lastDayOfTargetMonth);

  return new Date(targetYear, targetMonth, clampedDay);
}

// Tests
const cases = [
  ["2023-01-31", "2023-02-28"],
  ["2024-01-31", "2024-02-29"],
  ["2024-03-31", "2024-04-30"],
  ["2024-02-29", "2024-03-29"],
];

for (const [input, expected] of cases) {
  const actual = addOneCalendarMonth(new Date(input + "T00:00:00"));
  const actualIso = actual.toISOString().slice(0, 10);
  console.assert(actualIso === expected, `${input} -> ${actualIso}, expected ${expected}`);
}

console.log("All tests passed.");
```

So the defined rule is:

> **When the target month has fewer days, clamp to that month’s last valid day rather than overflowing into the following month.**

