838.answer:
Use an iterative parser with explicit stacks, not recursive descent.

### Approach
- Tokenize digits, operators `+ - * /`, and parentheses.
- Parse/evaluate with the **shunting-yard** pattern or two-stack precedence parser.
- Track `parenDepth` as an integer and reject if it exceeds `50000`.
- Maintain parser state to reject malformed input:
  - `()` → empty parentheses
  - `1 ++ 2`, `1 + * 2` → adjacent operators
  - `(+)`, `(*2)` → operator where operand expected
  - `2(3+4)` → missing operator
  - `1 2` → missing operator
  - unmatched `(` or `)`

### State machine
Keep a boolean like `expectOperand`:
- Initially `true`
- When reading:
  - **number**: valid only if `expectOperand === true`, then set `false`
  - **(**: valid only if `expectOperand === true`, increment depth, push marker, keep `true`
  - **operator**: valid only if `expectOperand === false`, then set `true`
  - **)**: valid only if `expectOperand === false`; this also rejects empty `()`

At end:
- valid only if `expectOperand === false`
- no unmatched parentheses remain

### Example implementation (JavaScript)

```js
function evaluateExpression(input, maxDepth = 50000) {
  const values = [];
  const ops = [];
  let i = 0;
  let depth = 0;
  let expectOperand = true;

  const precedence = (op) => (op === '+' || op === '-') ? 1 : 2;

  const applyOp = () => {
    if (ops.length === 0) throw new Error('Malformed input');
    const op = ops.pop();
    if (op === '(') throw new Error('Malformed input');

    if (values.length < 2) throw new Error('Malformed input');
    const b = values.pop();
    const a = values.pop();

    switch (op) {
      case '+': values.push(a + b); break;
      case '-': values.push(a - b); break;
      case '*': values.push(a * b); break;
      case '/':
        if (b === 0) throw new Error('Division by zero');
        values.push(a / b);
        break;
      default:
        throw new Error('Malformed input');
    }
  };

  while (i < input.length) {
    const ch = input[i];

    if (ch === ' ' || ch === '\t' || ch === '\n' || ch === '\r') {
      i++;
      continue;
    }

    if (ch >= '0' && ch <= '9') {
      if (!expectOperand) throw new Error('Malformed input');

      let num = 0;
      while (i < input.length && input[i] >= '0' && input[i] <= '9') {
        num = num * 10 + (input.charCodeAt(i) - 48);
        i++;
      }
      values.push(num);
      expectOperand = false;
      continue;
    }

    if (ch === '(') {
      if (!expectOperand) throw new Error('Malformed input');
      depth++;
      if (depth > maxDepth) throw new Error('Max parenthesis depth exceeded');
      ops.push(ch);
      i++;
      continue;
    }

    if (ch === ')') {
      if (expectOperand) throw new Error('Malformed input'); // rejects empty ()
      while (ops.length > 0 && ops[ops.length - 1] !== '(') {
        applyOp();
      }
      if (ops.length === 0 || ops[ops.length - 1] !== '(') {
        throw new Error('Malformed input');
      }
      ops.pop();
      depth--;
      i++;
      expectOperand = false;
      continue;
    }

    if (ch === '+' || ch === '-' || ch === '*' || ch === '/') {
      if (expectOperand) throw new Error('Malformed input'); // rejects adjacent operators
      while (
        ops.length > 0 &&
        ops[ops.length - 1] !== '(' &&
        precedence(ops[ops.length - 1]) >= precedence(ch)
      ) {
        applyOp();
      }
      ops.push(ch);
      i++;
      expectOperand = true;
      continue;
    }

    throw new Error(`Invalid character: ${ch}`);
  }

  if (expectOperand) throw new Error('Malformed input');

  while (ops.length > 0) {
    if (ops[ops.length - 1] === '(') throw new Error('Malformed input');
    applyOp();
  }

  if (values.length !== 1) throw new Error('Malformed input');
  return values[0];
}
```

### Why this avoids overflow
- No recursive calls
- Parentheses are handled by stack pushes/pops
- Depth 50,000 is just stack array growth, not call stack growth

### Malformed inputs rejected
- `()`
- `( )`
- `1++2`
- `1+*2`
- `+1`
- `1+`
- `((3))`
- valid
- `2(3+4)`
- `1 2`
- `)(`
- `((1+2)`

